
[1]olympiad

   OLYM'PIAD, n. [L. Olympias; Gr. from Olympus, a mountain of Macedonia.]

   A period of four years reckoned from one celebration of the Olympic
   games to another, and constituting an important epoch in history and
   chronology. The first Olympiad commenced 775 years before the birth of
   Christ, and 22 years before the foundation of Rome. The computation by
   Olympiads ceased at the three hundred and sixty fourth Olympiad, in the
   year 440 of the christian era.
